## table card | under=tpl_project | doc="Template predicate-snippet cards — every newly stamped project inherits 'Overdue', 'Due within 3 days', and 'Heads' as named filters. The two date snippets reference the relative-date ops (before_today / within_days) which the server compiler resolves against now()::date at query time so the result keeps moving with the clock instead of going stale on save. The non-terminal status check is expressed as has_phase [triage, active] (the kernel form) so the advanced filter editor renders the operator with its friendly label. 'Heads' surfaces tasks with no parent OR whose parent has reached terminal, i.e. the current 'head of chain' view. This is the LAST template card block, so it carries reset_sequence=card_id_seq: every template card above is inserted with an EXPLICIT id, so the sequence must be advanced past them here (after the final insert). Without this a fresh non-demo seed leaves card_id_seq behind the template ids and the first runtime card insert collides (card_pkey). Demo doesn't hit this — its later cards use auto-ids that advance the sequence naturally." | on_conflict="id" | reset_sequence=card_id_seq
### rows
id, card_type_id,                 parent_card_id, title,                  predicate
28, $card_type.predicate_snippet, parent,         "Overdue",              `{"connective":"and","children":[{"attr":"status","op":"has_phase","values":["triage","active"]},{"attr":"due_date","op":"before_today"}]}`
29, $card_type.predicate_snippet, parent,         "Due within 3 days",    `{"connective":"and","children":[{"attr":"status","op":"has_phase","values":["triage","active"]},{"attr":"due_date","op":"within_days","values":[3]}]}`
30, $card_type.predicate_snippet, parent,         "Heads",                `{"connective":"or","children":[{"attr":"parent_task","op":"not exists"},{"attr":"parent_task","op":"has_phase","values":["terminal"]}]}`


